metadata.name: Mandelroid #64
metadata.description:
The Mandelbrot set is a mathematical object that is generated by a simple formula, and it exhibits some interesting visual patterns that are reminiscent of those found in nature, such as the self-similarity of branching structures, the repetition of small-scale patterns on larger scales, and the presence of chaotic behavior.

The beauty of Polaroid film lies in its ability to capture and preserve a moment in space and time in a unique and tangible way.

This work combines two things that are incongruent with each other and brings them together to create a digital memory that serves as a reminder that complexity can be found even in the simplest things, that art is intrinsic to nature itself.

• press '1' to scale the photo to 1024x1024 pixels (the default output)
• press '2' to scale the photo to 2048x2048 pixels (Warning: can be slow!)
• press '3' to scale the photo to 4096x4096 pixels (Warning: can be very slow!)
• press 'd' to save the Mandelbrot Set
• press 's' to save the Polaroid film

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | @outertales | December 2022

metadata.name: Clutch #21
metadata.description:
Halftones, dynamic composition and high color contrasts for a groovy composition inspired by action b-movies, their posters and music.

Semi-realtime javascript / webgl.
Desktop / Chrome recommended.

You can find more infos about the project in the fx(text) linked below.

Controls :
- Press [SPACE] to show/hide the user interface
- Mouse wheel/middle/ Pinch : Zoom
- After zooming, Mouse left / Drag : Pan

Keyboard shortcuts and additionnal instructions : 
- [R]eset the camera.
- Toggle the [F]rame.
- Unlock the [C]amera, with rotation on Mouse2.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys [1] to [9] (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). I recommend starting with [4] and going from there. What is captured is what's on screen, so you can get creative if you so desire.

NFT License

metadata.name: Continuum #92
metadata.description:
This project is the culmination of many generative art experiments I have run throughout 2022. It relies heavily on the random walks through color and space techniques I have been working with, but also introduces other elements related to 2D and 3D rotation, framing and grains.

Continuum began as an abstract composition made up of a set of interacting elements against a background. This is still true. However, in my own mind, I have come to consider many Continuum pieces as peculiar, stylized observations of massive futuristic spacial, or quantum, constructions. Maybe even involving a wormhole through the fabric of space-time for some civilization well past 1 on the Kardashev scale. At the center is an erratic crystalline form, which is fed by power trains, and all around is a massive multicolored rotating containment structure.

Aside from the standard, inverse, threshold and washed types, the most defining trait of each composition is the “Back Style” which relates to a point of construction, activity or deconstruction of these structures. This is further refined by the panel style, the panel density and the rotation level. The other traits largely relate to color variability and aesthetics. 

This work has been coded using p5.js, and half of all royalties from the primary, and secondary, sales are assigned to the processing foundation.

Press s to download a 2400x2400 pixel image.

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: Coronado #194
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #106
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.

metadata.name: Magic Board II #9
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Florescence #239
metadata.description:
Digitally crafted flowers in pots for virtual window sills.

In the spirit of the piranha plant from the Mario Bros videogame. We wanted to create a project that acknowledges the playful depiction of nature in early videogames by creating a retro futuristic collectible that explores aesthetics over gameplay, whilst preserving the playful energy of these early digital worlds. There are many game elements that have emerged over the years that have become iconic in their own right. Their memorable designs have come to represent the exciting feeling of when we first discovered these worlds, but over time an appreciation for their simple design execution, harmony and balance has emerged. Art can exist in many forms and places including a digital pot plant.

Rarity:

There are a total of 23 hand-drawn and animated sprites divided into 4 groups Firelillies, Flytraps, Quasars and Stargazers and there are 15 possible combinations made from these 4 groups. 18% of the collection is a combination of these 4 groups which we can call random and the remaining 72% is divided between the remaining 14 combinations.


There are 3 possible grid systems 1x1, 3x3 and 4x4 

3% 1x1

40% 3x3

57% 4x4



There are 14 possible placement points for all grids and 76 stem/sprite arragement in total



For the pots and stems there are 11 colors to choose and  no rarities for color combinations.



The flower distribution can be either symmetric or random. 35% symmetric and 65% random



Export options:

Pressing 's' on desktop or holding for 2 seconds will download gif to whatever the current device resolution is. To export at a different resolution open the token in new window by clicking 'open' link under the token image and add "&exportsize=1080" or "&exportsize=2160" to end of the url and hit enter then either hold for 2 seconds or press 's' to create gif and download.

metadata.name: System α #116
metadata.description:
"To capture the fleeting time in the generating process."

In this work,I d'like focus on the generating of generative art system itself rather than imitate some scene or style.
And with the flow of time, try to figure out where it can take me toward.

This work would be a series of my alternative view on generative art.
"α" means the first step of this series.

Press [s] in live view to save file as PNG.
Press [p] to stop.

------
Happy first birthday fx(hash) !!

20% of primary revenues go to Savepakistan Flood Relief Fundraiser.
20% of primary revenues go to the Processing foundation.

metadata.name: You Name It #11
metadata.description:
There are many questions and theories surrounding the magical mechanism of visual perception and how it is linked to our brain processing. 

How much knowledge we learn through perception is based on prior knowledge? 
How much of our perception do we receive directly, and how much do we infer? 

The brain combines external signals when a person explores their environment, leading to the perception of a persistent object. Even though an object is out of sight, it can still be remembered in mind via creative processes. 

When stimuli are spatially and temporally adjacent to one another, they may aggregate perceptually into prominent, coherent patterns or wholes. Our perceptual world is full of what we call a "gestalt, such as when leaves and branches group together to form trees and when trees combine to form forests; when eyes, ears, noses, and mouths arrange themselves into faces; when musical notes combine to form chords and melodies; and when countless dots or pixels come together to form a photograph. Our project is, in a sense challenge of perception, so what do you see? What comes into your mind as a perception when you look at it ??

Wait a moment it takes a while to be rendered
---
Created using vanilla javascript
KrouniHatim - Nov22
---
(CC BY-ND 4.0)
